The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     CRICKET BRIEFS
                                              Pak fined   for slow over rate  Calcutta: Pakistan were fined for slow over rate during their 140-run defeat against India in the tri-series in Dhaka on Tuesday, says A Staff Reporter. Match Referee Jeff Crowe imposed the fine after Shoaib Malik rsquo;s men were ruled to be two overs short when time allowances were taken into consideration. In accordance with the ICC Code of Conduct, players are fined five per cent of their match fees for every over, with the captain fined double that amount.  Dilip post  Calcutta: National selection committee chairman Dilip Vengsarkar has refused to confirm or deny a report that he would be the Indian Premier League (IPL) director (cricket operations) after completing his term in September, says A Staff Reporter. ldquo;I don rsquo;t wish to make a comment, rdquo; he said on Wednesday. IPL chairman and commissioner Lalit Modi refused to take calls.  BCCI meet  Calcutta: In the presence of captain Mithali Raj and vice-captain Jhulan Goswami, a meeting was recently organised at the BCCI headquarters in Mumbai under the chairmanship of secretary Niranjan Shah to discuss issues pertaining to women rsquo;s cricket. Also among the attendees were former India captains Diana Eduljee and Shanta Rangaswamy, says A Staff Reporter.   Sachin stint  London: Ahead of Team India rsquo;s tour of Sri Lanka, Sachin Tendulkar will play three matches for the Lashings World XI, the club said in a statement. Sachin would play the matches as part of his build-up for the tour, chairman David Folb said. His first match is scheduled on June 24 at Eastbourne College.  Bhonsle wish  New Delhi: Melody queen Asha Bhonsle will soon invite cricketing icon Sachin Tendulkar to sing with her and she is confident that the master batsman will not say ldquo; no rdquo; to her. ldquo;As I have said earlier that I want to sing with Sachin. I have not spoken to him on this matter. He is so busy rdquo; she said.  Stanford ties  London: England cricketers will take part in some of the richest matches in sport after it was announced on Wednesday that they would be playing a series of $20 million winner-takes all Twenty20 clashes in the Caribbean. The matches are being sponsored by Texan billionaire Allen Stanford.  Samuels rsquo; hope   Melbourne: Awaiting the ICC rsquo;s decision on a two-year ban imposed on him, West Indies batsman Marlon Samuels said he is confident of being cleared and is looking forward to be back in the side for the ODI series against Australia. ldquo;I need to start playing as soon as possible. If it could be the series against Australia, that would be fantastic, rdquo; he said.   Asif setback  Karachi: Pakistani pacer Mohammed Asif rsquo;s wait in detention is set to extend another week as the attorney general rsquo;s office in Dubai has not yet submitted the report on his drug possession case to the public prosecutor.
                                                                                                                                                               
